23. And Adam lived one hundred and thirty years after a course of male hormones. He was lifted on and off and, lo, he begat a son, Seth, who went on to begat many sons and daughters and won the Queen's Award for Industry.

24. Seth lived one hundred and five years and, after testosterone tablets, begat Enos.

25. And it came to pass, men began to multiply on the face of the earth - and lo, there were many queues for hip operations and standing only on the tube.

26. And the sons of God saw the daughters of men and they were fair; and they took them all wives all of which they chose, but woe, the sleeping arrangements were dodgy.

27. There were giants on the earth in those days; they were all in the British Rugby Team.

28. The Lord looked upon the earth, and lo, it was corrupted with Nightmare on Elm Street III.

29.He sayeth unto Noah, "Build an Ark and two of every animal upon the earth thou shalt take in it." So Noah let the animals in, and lo, Noah and his family were soon up to their necks in it. And Noah's wife said, "For God's sake - somebody open a window."

30. And the Lord made it rain forty days and nights and the world was flooded, all except England where they had drought and a hosepipe ban.

31. And the rain and the waters prevailed upon the earth a hundred and fifty days and woe, cricket was cancelled at the Oval.

32. And it came the waters abated, and Noah sent forth a raven - yea, he went forth and stayed forth. 

33. Noah then sent forth a dove, and lo, it returned with an olive leaf plucked off. Noah himself was pretty plucked off.

34. Noah waiteth seven days and he sendeth off the dove yet again - but this time it returned not, having been shot on the Glorious Twelfth.

35. And when the land had dried, Noah lifted the cover off the Ark and let it all out.

Chapter III, part 2

17. And it came to pass that Cain rose up and slew Abel very badly.

18. And the Lord said, "Ello, 'ello , 'ello, what's going on 'ere?"

19. And the Lord set a mark upon Cain - it was on his right arm and said Man. United.

20. And Cain went out from Eden to the land of Nod, but there was a curse on the land; it was called Nationwide Building Society.

21. And Cain knew his wife and she bore him a child, Enoch, and in the goodness of time they were all in B & B.

22. But Cain was wise and applied for child benefit.

Chapter III, (part 1)

1. Now the serpent was more subtle than the beasts of the field; he said unto the woman: 'Come and eat the fruit of this tree.' Woman said, 'Nay, if we eat or touch it we die.' And the serpent said, 'Fear not, they are not from South Africa,' whereupon she ate and gave of it to her husband.

2. And the eyes of them both were opened and they knew they were both naked, and Adam said to her, 'Stand back, I don't know how big this is going to get.'

3. And the Lord God called unto Adam: 'Where art thou?'

4. And Adam said, 'I art here.'

5. But both Adam and Eve's eyes were opened and they saw they were naked and they sewed on fig leaves - one for Eve and a hundred and eighty for Adam.

6. The Lord said, 'Who told thee that thou wast naked?'

7. And Adam said, ' I could see it all hanging down.'

8. 'Hast thou eaten of the apple?' said the Lord.

9. 'Yea, Eve gave it to me,' said Adam. 'A Granny Smith.'

10. 'Woman,' said the Lord, 'what hast thou done?'

11. And Eve said, 'I haven't done anything, I've only just got here.'

12. And the Lord said unto the serpent, 'Because thou hast done this, thou art cursed above all cattle, and above every beast of the field; upon thy belly thou shalt go, and dust shalt thou eat all the days of your life.'

13. 'This is victimisation,' said the serpent; 'I shall appeal to the RSPCA'

14. Unto Adam and Eve the Lord God made coats of skins and, verily, they looked terrible - you could still see it all.

15. And Eve saw Cain and said, 'Lo, I have gotten a man from the Lord.'

16. And she got another son and together they were called Cain and Abel.

CHAPTER II

 

1. On the seventh day God ended His work, but Datsun of Coventry workers went on to time and a half, and God rested from all His work with complete backing from Arthur Scargill and the miners.

2. God blessed the seventh day, as did all the Pakistani corner shops.

3. Every plant, every herb was in earth for the Good Lord had not caused it to rain; because of this Bob Geldof had to raise fifty million quid with LiveAid.

4. And the Lord formed man of the dust of the ground, and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life; it was done privately and not on the National Health.

5. The Lord planted a garden in Eden and there He put the man He had formed, and He sold the idea to the BBC as  Gardener's World.

6. And out of the ground the Lord grew every tree that was pleasant to the sight, but He had not reckoned on the weather forecast from Michael Fish, and they were all blown down in the hurricane.

7. And the Lord took man and put him in the Garden of Eden to dress it and to keep it, subject to compulsary purchase by Brent Council.

8. The Lord God said, of every tree in the garden thou mayest freely eat, but He was apprehended at the checkout and forced to pay.

9. But of the tree of knowlege, thou shalt not eatest, or thou shal surely die, due to crop-spraying with DDT.

10. And the Lord said, it is not good that man should be alone. He caused a great sleep to fall upon Adam, which the shop steward penalised him for during working hours, deducting a day's pay. The Lord took one of Adam's ribs, and made a woman, and brought her unto the man, which immediately qualified for common law wife allowance.

11. And they were both naked, the man and his wife, and were not ashamed. However, at Bow Street they were charged with indecency.

Every day I will put a chapter of this book, 'The Bible according to Spike Milligan', on my LiveJournal, in the hope that it will provide some people with amusement.

Chapter 1

THE CREATION ACCORDING TO THE TRADE UNIONS

1. In the beginning God created the Heaven and the Earth.

2. And darkness was upon the face of the deep, and this was due to a malfunction at Lots Road Power Station.

3. And God said, Let there be light; and there was light, but Eastern Electricity Board said He would have to wait until Thursday to be connected.

4. And God saw the light and it was good; He saw the quarterly bill and that was not good.

5. And God called the light Day, and the darkness He called Night, and so passed his GCSE.

6. And God said, Let there be a firmament and God called the firmament heaven, Freephone 999.

7. And God said, Let the waters be gathered together in one place, and let the dry land appear; and in London it went on the market at six hundred pounds a square foot.

8. And God said, Let the earth bring forth grass, and the earth brought forth grass and the Rastafarians smoked it.

9. And God said, Let there be lights in heaven to give light to the earth, and it was so, except over England where there was heavy cloud and snow on high ground.

10. And God said, Let the seas bring forth that which hath life, flooding the market with fishfingers, fishburgers and grade-three salmon.

11. And God blessed them, saying, Be fruitful, multiply and fill the sea, and let fowl multiply on earth where Prince Charles and Prince Philip would shoot them.

12. And God said, Let the earth bring forth cattle and creeping things, and lo, there came cows, and the BBC Board of Governers.

13. And God said, Let us make man in our own image, but woe many came out like Spitting Image.

14. And He said, Let man have dominion over fish, fowl, cattle and every creepy thing that creepeth upon the earth.

15. And God said, Behold, I have given you the first of free yielding seed; to you this shall be meat, but to the EC it shall be a Beef Mountain.

I had the most weird dream last night. I have just received an invite to the staff christmas party, at the college, and I dreamt that the assistant supervisor said that I couldn't go, as she needed me to work that night. I woke up soon after telling her she could stuff her need for staff that night where it ought to be: up the Khyber Pass!!!!

Anyway, today we brought the ponies up to the yard again, and then we had breakfast and I did some baking. I made a christmas pudding, some coconut macaroons, and a lemon drizzle cake. I'm still waiting for that to finish baking. Then, after a drink, we made some doughnuts, but something must have gone wrong with the mix, because the sugar wouldn't stick. But they taste ok, so something went right!

Later when we took the ponies back to the field, we gave them their hay & water, but then found the damn lock wouldn't click shut! So we had to go and borrow a hammer from Maggie to hammer it shut. I WISH Dad would change the padlock on the gate. It's becoming so stiff to close.

We went to High Wycombe today, and saw the reindeer in the John Lewis store. They were lovely. 2 of them, one called Belle and the other Jingle. Also there was a miniature shetland called Mickey Mouse - silly name really -  and a Dorset Down sheep called Doris.

I've just had a call from Robert, at the college. Tomorrow's going to be fairly quiet, so I don't have to work! A Sunday being an actual day of rest! Lovely!

I managed to catch the second episode of M*A*S*H tonight, but missed the first, so I'll watch it tomorrow.
